'''Scipuar''' ({{lang-el|Σκιποῦαρ}}, {{fl.|ca. 551–552}}) was a commander of the [[Ostrogoths]] in the final stages of the [[Gothic War (535–554)|Gothic War]] against the [[Eastern Roman Empire]].

[[Procopius]] mentions Scipuar along with [[Gibal]] and [[Indulf (6th century)|Indulf]] (Gundulf) as "the most notable among the [[Goths]]." Together with the other two he was appointed commander by [[Totila]] and ordered to capture [[Ancona]] in [[Picenum]].{{sfn|Dewing|1962|pp=287, 289}}{{sfn|Martindale|Jones|Morris|1992|p=1118}} While Gibal and Indulf assumed command of naval forces, Scipuar led the siege of the city. After Gibal and Indulf suffered a crushing defeat at the [[Battle of Sena Gallica (551)|Battle of Sena Gallica]] in the fall of 551, Scipuar's army retreated from Ancona to [[Osimo|Auximum]], enabling the Byzantine commander Valerian to assume control of the city.{{sfn|Martindale|Jones|Morris|1992|p=1118}}{{sfn|Dewing|1962|p=291}} 

Scipuar fought side by side with Totila at the disastrous [[Battle of Taginae]] in 552. Along with other four men, he accompanied Totila during his flight from the battlefield. A party of Roman soldiers pursued them and caught up with them, killing Totila. Scipuar managed to wound Totila's killer [[Asbadus]], but was wounded in turn. The Romans then gave up the pursuit and left them alone. Nothing further is known of Scipuar thereafter.{{sfn|Martindale|Jones|Morris|1992|p=1118}}{{sfn|Dewing|1962|pp=383, 385}}

